A black box in your car?
While U.S. road planners are struggling to find the money needed to repair the downhill highway infrastructure, many see a solution in the form of a small black box that sits above your car’s dashboard.
The aircraft, which record all the miles traveled by a driver and pass on information to officials, are at the center of a controversial attempt in Washington and in government planning offices to reform the outdated system of funding major U.S. roads.
The generally uninterested sector of major axis planning has suddenly sparked heavy debate and hectic alliances.
Libertarians have joined environmental groups to pressure the government to use the small boxes to keep track of the miles you’re traveling, and possibly the road you’re traveling on, and then use the information to draft a tax bill.
The Tea Party has landed.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also very concerned and expresses its concern about privacy protection.
And while members of Congress can't agree on whether to continue, several states haven't waited.
They are looking at how, over the next decade, they will be able to switch to a system that allows drivers to pay based on the number of miles traveled.
Thousands of drivers have already embarked on these black boxes, sometimes equipped with a GPS monitoring system, for an experimental trip.
This is truly indispensable for our nation.
“It’s not like we have a choice,” said Hasan Ikhrata, managing director of the Southern California Association of Governments, who predicts that the state will begin recording the miles traveled by each Californian driver by 2025.
There will be change in the way we pay these taxes.
Technology is here to do this.
The pressure comes from the fact that the country’s Highway Trust Fund, funded with the taxes Americans pay at the pump, is financially dry.
Americans are no longer buying as much gasoline as before.
Cars can travel more miles with a gallon.
The federal tax itself, which is 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Politicians are reluctant to raise the tax, even by one cent, while gasoline prices are high.
“The fuel tax is simply not sustainable,” said Lee Munnich, a transport policy specialist at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently installed tracers on 500 cars to test a mile payment system.
“This turns out to be the most logical long-term alternative,” he said.
Wonks calls this a mileage fee.
It is not surprising that the idea seduces urban liberals, as taxes could be used to change driving habits so as to reduce congestion and gas emissions, for example.
California planners are interested in the system as they develop strategies to achieve the goals set in the state’s ambitious global warming laws.
But Representative Bill Shuster (R-Pa), Chairman of the House Transport Committee, said he also regarded it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The Reason Foundation’s supporters of the free market also appreciate the idea of making drivers pay for the mile.
“It’s not just a tax going into a big black hole,” said Adrian Moore, vice president of politics at the Reason Foundation.
People pay more directly for the benefits they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. Transport Secretaries who, in a 2011 report, urged Congress to go on the mile payment path.
The U.S. Senate approved a pilot project of $90 million last year that allegedly covered about 10,000 cars.
But the chairman of the House killed the proposal, responding to the concerns of rural legislators representing voters who have to travel many miles every day to go to their work or to the city.
However, several states and major cities are making progress on their side.
The most determined is Oregon, which has mobilized 5,000 drivers to carry out the country's most important experience.
These drivers will soon pay the state kilometer fees instead of gasoline taxes.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
The city of New York is considering one.
Illinois tries a test on a limited number of trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which comprises 17 agencies involved in road transport in states along the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is studying how it could implement the change.
The concept is not a universal success.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer drivers have recently equipped their cars with an aircraft, drivers were worried that the government could follow their slightest actions and actions.
“The concerns about Big Brother and things like that are a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, who leads strategic performance management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It's not something people want.
At the beginning of the test, the Nevada ACLU warned on its site: “It would be relatively easy to turn these devices into full-fledged location devices.”
There is no need to build a huge and bulky technological infrastructure that will inevitably be expanded to keep records of people’s daily coming and runways.
Nevada is one of the few states now working to find affordable technology that would allow the state to know how many miles a car is traveling, but without knowing the exact location or time.
If we can do that, Khan added, citizens will be more comfortable.
Research on this technology led some state agencies to call on a small California start-up named True Mileage.
Originally, the company was not intended to help motorists paying taxes to states.
She sought to penetrate the emerging car insurance market, in which drivers would pay based on their mileage.
But the devices it tests have liked large-axis planners because they do not use GPS and provide a limited amount of information, periodically downloaded by modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don’t record their speed and locate them,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
Serious mistakes have been made in the pilot programmes of some States.
There are much less expensive ways and much less intrusive methods to proceed.
In Oregon, planners try the experience by offering drivers different choices.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
They may still choose not to have an appliance at all, preferring instead to pay a package based on the average number of miles traveled by all residents of the state.
Other states hope to sell the concept to suspicious citizens by allowing the devices to do more, rather than not enough.
In New York City, transport officials are looking to develop a taxation system that would also be equipped to pay parking fees, provide “payment at driving” insurance, and create a set of real-time speed data from other drivers that drivers could use to avoid traffic jams.
“Autors would be encouraged to participate because of the benefits that the system offers them,” said a document on urban planning.
However, some transport planners wonder whether the whole debate on mile payment is not just a huge diversion.
At the San Francisco Bay Area Metropolitan Transportation Commission, officials say Congress could very simply manage the bankruptcy of the Highway Trust Fund by raising gasoline taxes.
A single or additional annual tax could be imposed on drivers of hybrid vehicles and others whose vehicles do not consume much gasoline, so each one pays his fair share.
“It’s not necessary to resort to radical surgery when you simply need aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, Director of Legislation and Public Affairs at the Commission.
If we do that, hundreds of millions of drivers will worry about protecting their privacy and a bunch of other things.
David Bowie: Four Unreleased Listen
The English musician hasn’t finished surprised this year.
Starting with The Next Day, released in January, he concocted a luxury re-edition scheduled for November 4, with several new releases.
Four have already emerged on the web.
The announcement of the release of a new album by David Bowie had left everyone in a row.
On his 66th birthday, January 8, 2013, he said a new album would be released in March.
After ten years of silence (the last record, Reality, dated 2003) and too rare public appearances, the English musician proved that he could still be relied on to make the pop scene shimmer.
A feast for its fans
Not tired of surprises, David Bowie had more than one round in his bag with The Next Day.
The Thin White Duke planned to re-release this album on November 4.
For the occasion, he made a real feast for his fans.
This re-edition, entitled The Next Day Extra, will be presented in the form of three records: the original album, unreleased studio sessions and remixes, as well as a DVD containing the four previously released clips.
The Next Day Extra will contain a total of ten additional tracks compared to the original album: the three tracks from the Deluxe edition, five songs specially unveiled for the occasion, as well as two remixes.
David Bowie also made the presentations of this beautiful box in a video.
He introduces both the discs, but also the accessories supplied with: exclusive photos and covers, a notebook to share his own impressions, a booklet with the lyrics...
And, above all, he gives a taste of his new Atomica track, typically in The Next Day’s vein, with very forward guitars and a skillfully mastered rock electricity.
Unprecedented news already on listening
But Atomica is not the only title to reveal its charms.
The Informer, Like A Rocket Man, Born In A UFO are also available on the web.
The Informer is double-faced: a worrying intro before a luminous cavalcade that gradually slows down to leave room for a pop ballad.
Like A Rocket Man, did Bowie want to make a little reference to Elton John’s Rocket Man, or even Gravity?
With this playful title, the singer seems at least in his element when he no longer has feet on the ground.
Space Oddity, next door, was much more serious.
On Born In A UFO, David Bowie once again refers to his strangeness: would he come from another planet?
The enchanting guitar riffs make you want to leave the Earth.
Bowie has fun playing the chameleon with these titles: informant turn-to-turn, man aboard a rocket, Martian potential...
He conceals and reveals at the same time, plays to adopt different personalities, as he has done throughout his career, especially with his characters Ziggy Stardust and Aladdin Sane.
No wonder he has a mask in his hand in the photography of the campaign L'Invitation à Voyage, of the brand Louis Vuitton, whose new face he embodies.
It will appear in one of their advertising spots, broadcast from November 10.
Defence Minister Rob Nicholson insisted that the wounded soldiers were not summarily freed from the Canadian Armed Forces, and stressed that a transition process was being followed by all soldiers before they return to civilian life.
