Frontier Airlines plans to pay for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 to passengers carrying hand luggage on their flights.
Frontier Airlines is planning to start paying up to $100 for a hand luggage and $2 for a coffee or soda, although in its announcement on Wednesday, it indicated that passengers could carry the unopened can with them at the plane’s descent.
New hand luggage fees are for bags in the upper compartment, so small bags under the seat will always be free.
Frontier said it would pay $25 if the fee was paid in advance and $100 if travellers only pay once at the boarding gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 was planned to encourage travelers to pay the fees in advance.
“We don’t want to have that price paid,” she explained.
The airlines began paying for the first and second baggage checked in 2008.
Passengers trying to avoid these charges put as much as they could in hand luggage in the upper compartments, so there was often no space in those compartments.
These fees are a way to ensure that passengers carry less on board.
O'Malley said these new fees won't really be used to raise money.
It is about making the most loyal clients of Frontier understand that it is becoming increasingly difficult to find space in the upper compartments.
Passengers who buy their ticket on the airline’s website will not have to pay.
Thus, a passenger tailing at a Frontier boarding door could carry a bag for free, while the next person in the queue might have to pay $100 for a similar bag.
O'Malley explained that Frontier's site and registration procedures are changing to ensure that passengers are aware of these fees before arriving at the door.
Frontier hand luggage fees will not be charged before the summer, although no date has been fixed.
Passengers often bump about luggage fees and other charges, but airlines love them.
They believe that baggage handling costs are high and that passengers who want this service should pay it.
Many people on Wall Street view the addition of luggage fees as a sign that airlines are paying enough to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, many of them have not affected the baggage fees.
Spirit Airlines Inc. applied the first hand luggage fee three years ago, and the low-cost airline Allegiant followed a little later.
