Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of Southern Europe end up with an intrinsic productivity problem vis-à-vis Germany.
The only resort is to make dark cuts in wages and public spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper discomfort related to productivity in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German companies in the energy sector at the consumer expense – the European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as for gas as the US.
