Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and child health issues.
Should a mother worry if her daughter’s pubic breasts and hair start growing at age 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, Dr. Paul Kaplowitz, a pedo-endocrinologist, explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young Americans and represent a new standard.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – in general, this does not indicate a rapid evolution toward full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as budding of breasts, hair under the arms and in the pubic area and body odours, appear earlier in girls.
But there has only been a slight advance in the age of the first menstruation over the past four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, while it was 12 years three quarters in 1970.
“Once the breast has started to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first menstruation appears,” said Kaplowitz, also author of Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test for how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered “early” when breast development is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8 years.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – this is something a pediatrician can follow closely.
Faster evolution may justify testing by an endocrinologist to avoid serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the onset of early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone aging that can slow growth and small size in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug and hormone treatment are based on the child's age, development rate, growth rate and affective maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with medications but acknowledges that “controlling puberty can alleviate certain behavioural problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents simply don’t want their very young girls to have their menstruation.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even how they’re going to handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first menstruation at age 10.
Even if there were signs and we had talked about the rules, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She returned from school scared and upset to be the first of her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones contained in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages conveyed by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz claims that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study of girls aged 6 to 9 years that links the percentage of fat mass to the outbreak of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have younger hair on the face and in the pubic area, the tendency to true early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors participating in the PAA conference stressed the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be cautious about how we identify the true appearance of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a pedo-endocrinologist working at the Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“It may mean having a conversation earlier than expected,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you stay calm, your child will generally react well.
Girls whose puberty is early should be reassured that even when it happens earlier than expected, the process is part of life.
