How Biometrics Will Invade Our Lives
Do you have the passwords to type to access your smartphone or pay for your purchases?
American, French and Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, deputy general manager of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric."
Only biometrics will ensure the identity of a person carrying out transactions in a universe as transversal and transnational as the Internet.
Privacy organizations confirm this enthusiasm for biometrics, but are concerned.
In 2011 alone and in France, the National Commission of Computer Science and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for recognition of fingerprints, the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
“Everyone can soon be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy at the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, among some, and pessimism, among others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques that will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most widely used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
Each of these techniques has its own constraints.
“For example, some people who work concrete have fingers very damaged and their fingerprints are illegible,” said Philippe Robin, Technical Director of Identity at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand implies a voluntary and accurate gesture of the people.
This is both a security - we cannot capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
Consequently, research has been conducted for about twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the computing capacity of computers needed for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
Face recognition accuracy has increased tenfold over the past five years, according to Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
“Today, we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but it takes a quiet environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and prospective at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers a suitcase costing €90,000 to analyze DNA samples on the scene of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is who they claim to be).
The identification so far concerned the issue of identity documents: biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be confronted with the information that the state has on all citizens already registered.
This makes sure that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else’s identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
“We collect images from surveillance cameras and compare them to the photos of celebrities freely circulating on the Internet,” said Dany Nassif, head of business development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Another use: take a picture of a quidam that is in the queue in a store, track its progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
The authentication initially concerned physical access (border, protected premises, canteens...) or logical access (opening a computer).
More recently, presence control has been added to it.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend that pointes for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing your card and laying your hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the key of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and large-scale signs: when paying in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but inserts his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French merchants.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a customer remains in the box thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, reassure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
“Fingerprints are stored on a first server; people’s identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure enclosure, which blocks if you try to move it,” said Philippe Robin of Thales.
But lacking in-depth studies, it is impossible to know if these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to worry.
“The progress in facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, makes me fear the worst: widespread surveillance,” said Andrew Patrick, of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
