Scientists have just highlighted how a dog’s tail movements are linked to his mood.
Previous studies had shown that happy dogs moved their tail more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say dogs can detect these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: “Everyone knows that in man, the left and right side of the brain are differently involved in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions.”
Here, we tried to see what was going on with other species.
He added that, as in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain was responsible for moving to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to disordered tail movements from other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies with other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behaviour.
It will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We introduced dogs to movies with other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion – and we were able to trade the tail movement and present it as going more left or right.”
When the animals saw a dog without expression moving the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail mainly turning left (again from the point of view of the dog moving the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Instead, he thinks dogs know by experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you meet other dogs repeatedly and notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to that experience.”
The researchers say the results could enable owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a guest professor at the School of Veterinary Sciences at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team at Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs were easier to go to a robot dog when his tail was moving to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious—the opposite of what is stated in the Italian study.”
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs who participated in the different studies did not entirely regard film animals or robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many elements, collected from different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will certainly not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
