A team of biologists led by the New York Wildlife Conservation Society has identified a new species of bumpy dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, a scientific mission officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM), returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of bumpy dolphin surprise you?
This is good news, but I am not particularly surprised.
Although in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge of species classification science.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these progress in genetics and molecular biology challenge the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
In the early 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are challenged because of progress in genetics.
In the same way, two very morphologically close species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case for the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific bump dolphins and Atlantic bump whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this an important discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral outbreak or accidental capture arises in the region, we might have to deal with the extinction of a species rather than the local disappearance of a population of a more widely spread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of individuals on Earth, i.e. stock, and the possibility that it has to recover from neighboring stocks.
For the species Sousa chinensis, of which the population of the new discovered species is derived, its stock has automatically become weaker, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, closer ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It should be noted that the marine environment is the least known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, rather than knowing what lives in the Marian pit, just 11 kilometers from the sea surface.
More money is spent in searching for life on other planets than in marine research and it is time for this to change.
