Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents to Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second inspired by the famous piano solos Gymnopédies de Satie.
An evening that allows you to see the whole prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, as white, in the immense space that is the Maisonneuve Theatre, advances, with a profile, thin like a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, as a simple trait, takes its shape.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a row of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only hands and faces uncovered, wait on each side of the play area, rush when the next graph appears, embody it, run out.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is done as a solo relay, as a group in unison (a solo mass), as a large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Glory of the Morning", where Chouinard performed a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, placed online at the foreground.
This is the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussions and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace is always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance carpet, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a portion of Michaux' poem, monocord and monotone in the cree, and will continue dancing.
And the music to go back, and the sequence to go back.
This long and energetic discharge, if possible, ends up numbing and numbing.
As does the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are a few beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a force at Chouinard - such as the hair that gets numb or the black fabrics that elongate the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
It seems that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, has imposed herself, with her tics.
Result: the bodies appear flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux’s inks, like Gestalt’s shapes, open up a broader, more porous imagination than dance.
Only the end, in negative terms, with his dancers chopped by a stroboscopic light and white signs in a suddenly black theatre, touches magic.
The public loved it, the welcome was warm.
The Gymnopedia, after the intestine, is richer.
The scene is partly covered with gray, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in a abandoned house.
At the piano, dancers relay to play the scores.
Their touching music misguides give true fragility.
On stage, couples are in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small solos of transitions, moving sets, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffons appear, also familiar to Chouinard, with a red nose, in highly polarized male-women love parades.
Loves are carnivores, fleeing or players.
The gesture, laughter and small cries beautifully transpose the archaic, grace and ridicule of the bodies in coit, of beings that merge.
But the piece takes its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes on stage when the audience leaves.
There everything becomes allowed: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes overlap, the dancers cabotin, descend among the spectators, shine, smoke, short-circuit, play codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a wisely calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness sweat, and it is Chouinard's art to contaminate the public.
