He walks in mud, jungle and crosses rivers to offer free medical assistance
Dr. Georges Bwelle provides free health care in Cameroon villages
Dr. Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend seeing hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this West African country, only 1 per 5,000 inhabitants.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the 10 CNN Heroes of the Year 2013.
You can vote for him, or one of the other 10 heroes, to elect “CNN Hero of the Year.”
This person will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his sick father alternate periods of consciousness and unconsciousness and go to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a 1981 car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he had only one broken arm, but he contracted an infection that spread to his brain, creating a hematoma that he was going to bear the sequels for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals, so he could get any treatment he could benefit from.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle adds.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
For comparison, the ratio to the United States is 1 doctor per 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not afford the consultation.
Two in five people in the country live below the poverty threshold, and nearly three-quarters of the country’s health spending is in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” explained Dr. Bwelle.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and as many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed more than 700 surgical acts for free over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they sit in vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and cross difficult terrain to travel to the villages that need the most help.
Luck doesn’t always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed as heroes: the community organizes a party, sings and dance and offers them the best available accommodation.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to party, and Dr. Bwelle – with his big smile and overflowing energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team started receiving hundreds of patients.
“We receive 500 people every visit,” Bwelle said.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive buckets, a pair of collected glasses or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply can’t afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team performs simple surgical acts under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, town hall or house; after the procedure, the patient gets up and goes to the wake-up room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It's a busy pace, but village musicians generally help the team stay motivated.
“They’re hitting drums all night to keep us awake so we can continue to work,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 surgical acts for free over the past year, and it knows that their presence can make all the difference for those they come to help.
One man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
“It will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to living this traveling hospital and working as a surgeon in the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical facilities around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances its association to 60%; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteer with Dr. Bwelle’s group.
He is still in the hospital or is trying to find money for his association in order to be able to conduct these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O’Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is an opportunity for field learning that they don’t have at home.
“We were able to participate in operations to help sponge blood or hand over the instruments to Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explained.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a second-year medical student.
Volunteer students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transportation and teaching are handled by Dr. Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, there’s no doubt,” said Katie O’Malley.
He gave his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not near to extinguish.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others to live happily while keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle added.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieving pain are the reasons that push me to do this.
