In the spirit of Abdel-Malik Djermoune, its founder, the "Party of the suburbs" is not only addressed to the suburbs.
I chose a map of France as a logo, he justifies.
When I speak of suburbs, I address all those who are excluded from the great national family.
However, his project, presented Thursday at a press conference in his native municipality of Aubervilliers, was born of the will to better defend multiculturalism, this great cultural melting pot that characterizes above all the neighborhoods.
My proposal #1 is to create a ministry of multiculturalism, he says.
Abdel-Malik Djermoune, 50, a territorial attaché, now claims to be "100% apolitical" even though he has not always been neutral.
Militant in 2002 alongside Jean-Pierre Chevénement, he then supported Dominique de Villepin locally between 2010 and 2011.
I know well that the values of equality that I advocate in my programme are linked to the left, but if the right-wing people are willing to support me, I will listen to them too, he continues.
There are only extremist parties I am not talking about.
In addition to multiculturalism, Abdel-Malik Djermoune has built his program - consultable on the Internet - from many topics that are supposed to speak to suburban residents and especially to young people: the right to vote for foreigners, the legalization of cannabis, the civil majority at 16 years of age, the rehabilitation of the function of building guardian...
It remains to find candidates to form lists and defend his ideas on the political scene."For the 2014 municipal elections, this is likely to be fair, he acknowledges."
It is a problem of time and money.
The Suburban Party should still be represented in Aubervilliers through my candidature and I hope in other cities as well.
Abdel-Malik Djermoune says he already has seven list heads in metropolitan France and Martinique.
"And the support emails I have received since yesterday have not all emanated from the suburbs," he said.
John Kerry admitted, unprecedentedly, that American espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
John Kerry said the U.S.’s defensive attitude toward his surveillance programs was scrambled by admitting, unprecedentedly, that on several occasions, espionage “had gone too far inappropriately.”
The Secretary of State also acknowledged that he, like Barack Obama, ruled on “autopilot” when a series of incendiary revelations from whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA’s spying activities emerged.
The leaks placed the U.S. government at the center of a diplomatic storm with its allies.
Speaking at a video-linked intergovernmental conference in London, Kerry said: “It is undeniable that the President, I and other members of the government have learned of certain things in automatic pilot mode because we had the possibility, from the Second World War to the difficult years of the Cold War, and then of course on September 11.
He then became the first high-ranking member of the U.S. government to admit that U.S. espionage had exceeded limits, but insisted that everyone's rights had not been violated.
He said: “In some cases, it went too far inappropriately.”
And the President is determined to try to clarify and make clear to the people that he is now conducting an in-depth review of these practices so that no one feels wrong.
I assure you that innocent people will not be the victims of abuse in this process.
Kerry insisted, however, that the NSA was a force acting for good and that its surveillance operations had saved many lives.
He added, “We are living in a new world where people are ready to blow up.”
There is a radical extremism in the world that is determined to try to kill people, explode them and attack governments.
What if you could intercept their communications and stop them before they act?
We have indeed prevented planes from falling, buildings from exploding, and people from being murdered because we were able to learn the facts in advance.
Meanwhile, U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to address concerns about the alleged U.S. espionage case and convince Europeans of the need to continue joint counter-terrorism efforts with the U.S., Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy from Connecticut said he spoke to members of the European Parliament and others this week and was worried about the threats they had raised about a possible withdrawal of counter-terrorism organizations due to the feeling of frustration arising from the National Security Agency’s surveillance.
“It is really important for the protection of national security in the United States that Europeans remain with us in mutual commitment in the fight against terrorism,” Murphy, a Democrat serving his first term, and chairman of the U.S. Senate’s subcommittee on European Affairs, said in an interview from Washington.
And I’m going to go to Europe to make them understand that we need to continue working together to fight terrorism, despite the anger provoked by the NSA programs.
The press reports that the NSA has captured millions of communications in Europe, which has undermined relations with some U.S. allies, but the agency’s director said this week that it was incorrect and that it was a misunderstanding because it was about metadata that NATO allies had collected and shared with the U.S.
Other revelations have reported documents released by Snowden that the NSA had intercepted data and communications from the cell phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and those of 34 other heads of state.
The director of intelligence services, James Clapper, justified the espionage of the allies by stating that it was necessary and that it was a common practice on both sides.
In this tumult atmosphere, Murphy said his office was organizing a Congress trip, which is expected to take place this year, and that he hoped that the delegation would include members of both parties and both chambers.
The names of the other participating legislators should be disclosed in the coming days.
He said the route remains to be defined.
Murphy said the purpose of this trip was to improve relationships, but also to show “loving firmness.”
He explained that European heads of state must be honest with their citizens about the type of espionage programs they have been applying themselves for years.
“We can change our surveillance programs to better protect the rights of Europeans, but they must also understand that we are not the only ones in the world to do espionage,” Murphy said.
In the meantime, Kerry plans to travel this weekend to the Middle East and Poland to manage the resentment generated by US strategies in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as US surveillance activities.
