Australian woman appeals her imprisonment sentence in Thailand
A 21-year-old Sydney resident, sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for wrongly claiming to have been assaulted by a taxi driver, appealed the judgment and was released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was first convicted by a Phuket Province Court on June 15 of false statements after telling Thai police that a local taxi driver, accompanied by two other men who controlled her, had assaulted her early Sunday, June 10.
However, video surveillance recordings later revealed that she had safely returned to her hotel after separating from her Australian boyfriend.
Phuket police interviewed Bamford for two days before they confessed to inventing the whole story.
She was detained in a local police station cell before the court hearing.
Bamford was sentenced to a 15-day imprisonment sentence in a low-security detention centre in the outskirts of Phuket rather than in a women's prison.
This is the daughter of former Australian rugby league player Peter Tunks, who appealed to the Canberra Foreign Ministry to help his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about her daughter's well-being and wanted her to return to Australia.
“We obviously have been through an anxious moment, but we hope to bring her home safely as soon as possible,” Tunks said.
Bamford appealed the judgment and was released after the payment of a bail of 50,000 bahts.
In Australia, the press said that in the meantime she was on vacation in the Krabi area in southern Thailand.
Thai court sources said Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket, but warned that the appeal could lead to an increase in the sentence of up to two years in prison and imprisonment in an adult prison.
However, after the recent murder of Michelle Smith, an Australian travel agent, in Phuket, Thailand may also seek to restore her deteriorated image to tourists, which could lead to acquittal.
French police will arrest fans of Anderlecht who have come otherwise than with RSCA cars
French police have decided to set strict rules regarding the meeting of the Royal Sporting Club of Anderlecht against Paris Saint-Germain set on Tuesday, Marie Verbeke, the spokeswoman for the Brussels midday police zone, said Friday.
Belgian RSCA supporters who want to go to this Champions League match will have to use the travel system set up by the RSCA.
"The bus convoy will be escorted by police from a former Rekem border post to the PSG stadium," the spokeswoman said.
The process will be the same for the return.
"If other supporters had an intention to travel to Paris by other means, the French police prefecture said that measures have been taken to proceed with arrests and even custodians," Verbeke said.
Living together in French, the challenge of the school commission Marguerite-Bourgeoys
At the Marguerite-Bourgeoys school board, 62% of students have a native language other than French.
This is what motivated a year ago a consultation with parents, students, teachers and educational staff to reflect on ways to better integrate students living on horseback riding among several cultures.
The school board has just unveiled its vision of “Living Together in French”.
The Vision Diversity organization has been walking in schools for a year to help students of all backgrounds discover common landmarks that are not limited to the French language.
The discovery of neighborhoods, our architecture, our places are landmarks.
Great names of writers, artists, whether they are of a strain or came from elsewhere.
Who are our builders?
“So we create projects so that they can identify with all of this,” says Vision Diversity Chairman Aïda Kamar.
Michel Venne, of the Institut du Nouveau Monde, identified several challenges for the school board.
"On the transmission, for example, of what Quebec culture is, the feeling of belonging, the support of staff in the transformations we are experiencing, within the student clientele," he said.
The school board Marguerite-Bourgeoys has created a research centre that will give tools to teachers who, too, sometimes come from elsewhere.
Rachida Azdouz, of the University of Montreal, will be the scientific director.
Preparing to manage a class in a North American, Quebec context.
“Different educational strategies, that’s the real need,” she sums up.
The research will focus on inclusion from all aspects: linguistic, school, social and cultural.
